         <div type="translation" resp="part:argr">
 <p>Hail! <foreign>Om</foreign> homage to Śiva!
<supplied reason="subaudible">The year of the</supplied> Śaka king 1200.
In the reign of the lord of the great earth, Indravarman, my lord, that lord of the great earth had one beautiful queen, namely the lady royal grand-child, princess Sūryalakṣmī, native of Cathiy Pāṇḍurāṅgeśa,<note>The same toponym also figures in <ref target="DHARMA_INSCIC00006.xml">C. 6.1</ref>, in only slightly different form.</note> born from the excellent <foreign>jā</foreign> Amvryak Vijaiya.<note>We more commonly find the Sanskrit expression <foreign>paramodbhava</foreign>, to express the excellent pedigree of a person thus designated, and  <foreign>udbhava di parama</foreign> seems to be an analytic equivalent of the same expression. Since <foreign>jā</foreign> is a marker of low status, some doubt remains about what is meant here.</note> See was beautiful in appearance. She knew all treatises and scriptures. She sought <supplied reason="explanation">? <foreign>dvah</foreign></supplied> the compassion of the lord of the great earth, Indravarman, my lord. After she installed sculptures of gods in the land of Vijaya for her parents and children, she gave all all means of subsistence. She came to give <foreign>cai</foreign><!--<note>Cf. <foreign>caitra</foreign> in C. 43?</note  --> in the city of Krauṅ Vauk for Pov Ājñā, her elder sibling.
</p>
         </div>
